Text: While this week has cleared up many uncertainties, as our group tried to finalize our design I realize how interconnected everything is.
Take this seemingly simple query as an example:  "How many discussions has a user made in a document?"
As it turns out, it's not just making a table and with a user id and a discussion count column.

We realized we also needed to think about when this query needs to be answered within the application flow, how fast it should be answered, whom this query is serving, and how often users ask this query or how often the application should answer it.

And then comes the problem of choosing an appropriate type, deciding where to carry out any aggregate analysis afterwards (inside the database or on the client side), and trying to think what credentials/data a user session should have to make the query possible in the first place.
Our client hardly thinks about these crucial underlying questions.
It's not his fault.
Rodney and Gloria (who's practically disappeared) are there to run the business.
I've never thought things would get so entangled as well.
Perhaps there's better design pattern here.
Perhaps not.
But my appreciation of software design grows everyday.
It's a craft that takes time and patience, truly.
It's a good thing that we stumbled upon an excellent data modelling course in Cassandra by the very company that maintains the database itself.
It almost feels like I'm learning COMP101 again, but this time it's non-relational.
We just finished making an entities-relationship model based on OB3 yesterday and Rodney's finally sent us some solid queries.
Everyone's brushing up on their CQL and related theories to get ready for next week.
Hopefully we'll have some tables ready for coding by next Tuesday, and then, if things go well, dive into making a prototype dashboard for a student user or admin user.
Regarding last week's goals, I'd say that I'm quite comfortable with the basics of Cassandra now and can start thinking at a slightly higher, design-oriented level.
Part of the goals for next week is already mentioned above, so I guess hopefully by the end of next week we will have started populating the tables with dummy data to begin testing.

I'd also like to code something in Python to automate the process of generating and inserting dummy data as well (like a function to generate a row, and then a higher-order-function that repeats a function n times).
Python's the choice because our group's using the Python Cassandra driver and it's fairly straightforward.
Even better, that could be paired up with a simple backend API (since Toto already knows some Python Flask) to better simulate the actual process.
Even if it doesn't work out, I personally think that whatever comes out of this mock backend could serve as a good validation test for our tables.
